# sp-npxq.4 — Web: spawn-view tab bar + per-session surfaces — Implementation Plan

> **For agentic workers:** REQUIRED SUB-SKILL: Use superpowers:subagent-driven-development (recommended) or superpowers:executing-plans to implement this plan task-by-task. Steps use checkbox (`- [ ]`) syntax for tracking.

**Goal:** Add a tab bar atop the spawn view so one spawn can surface N concurrent sessions (session #0 + agent/shell sessions), each in its own live surface, with all panels kept mounted for keep-alive.

**Architecture:** A pure Zustand store keyed by `session_id` holds the per-spawn session roster + per-acp-session transcript/turn/perm + per-session conn state. Each session panel is **always mounted** (keep-alive) and CSS-hidden when inactive; ACP panels (`AcpSessionPanel`→`ChatView`) and mosh panels (`TerminalView`) each **self-own their own WebSocket** (symmetric with today's TerminalView). Radix `Tabs` is used for the **strip only**; we host panels ourselves so we control mount/hide. App.tsx sheds its single-socket ACP logic (wsRef/openSession/applyFrame/items/turn/perm) into the store + `SpawnTabs`, keeping only spawn lifecycle.

**Tech Stack:** React 19, Zustand (new dep), `radix-ui` unified pkg (Tabs), partysocket (`ReconnectingSocket`), xterm + FitAddon, Vitest + @testing-library/react. The web talks to CP via the hand-written `unary()` JSON-fetch helper (`web/src/api/connect.ts`) — **there is no generated TS protobuf client**, so no codegen step is needed.

