# sp-npxq.3 — Node: launch/reap additional sessions in the running container — Implementation Plan

> **For agentic workers:** REQUIRED SUB-SKILL: Use superpowers:subagent-driven-development (recommended) or superpowers:executing-plans to implement this plan task-by-task. Steps use checkbox (`- [ ]`) syntax for tracking.

**Goal:** Fill in the deferred launch/reap in `attach.go` `createSession`/`closeSession` so the node can start and tear down additional sessions (mosh tui/shell + acp agents) inside an already-running spawn container, keyed by `(spawn_id, session_id)`, reusing the existing Pump/tmuxRelay paths.

**Architecture:** All container-boundary ops go through a new `sessionExec` seam (real impl shells out to `docker/crictl exec`; tests inject a fake — no docker needed). `createSession` reserves the session id + (for acp) a pool port **synchronously** on the single Attach receive goroutine, emits a STARTING roster, then launches **async** (`go a.launchSession`) so a slow `docker exec` + ACP handshake never blocks the control channel. mosh sessions = launcher-created detached transparent-tmux + a per-(spawn,session) `tmuxRelay`; acp sessions = launcher wrapped in a node-named detached tmux (so it is reapable by name) + a per-(spawn,session) `Pump` dialed at the pool port. `closeSession` reaps only that session; the container stays up.

**Tech Stack:** Go; `internal/node` (attacher/Pump/tmuxRelay/sessionRegistry), `internal/spawnlet` (Manager exec/dial helpers, `ExecPrefixFor`), `internal/runtime` (`AttachTCP`), `deploy/agent/launch` (frozen, sp-npxq.2 — invoked, not edited).

